title: For Sale/Trade:  DelTon FDE AR15: 3 gun competition setup $675 - $775
postcontent:
I purchased this AR to use in 3 gun competitions, but found that I'm not as comfortable (and thereby as fast) with this gun as I am with my old beater AR, so I'm sending this one down the line. It was built using a DelTon stripped lower, a Palmetto State Armory lower parts kit, a Palmetto State Armory stock kit, and a DPMS slick sided upper. The upper is a flat top, optic ready upper with a railed gas block and an A2 flash hider. The barrel has a 1/9 twist rate and is rated for 5.56 NATO. It also has a Mil-spec collapsible CTR stock which eliminates the wobble.

I've fired less than 75 rounds through it (a few to sight it in, then two stages in a 3 gun competition before swapping to my other AR), so the round count is probably closer to 50 than 75. I've never had any problems out of this gun, and I'm sure with some practice I'd shoot this AR better than my other, but I'd rather just pass this one along and use the money to upgrade my optics.

I'm offering this rifle in one of two set ups, to accommodate various budgets:

$775 - Rifle with FDE Magpul CTR stock, FDE Magpul MOE grip, FDE Magpul MOE hand guard, and 1 FDE Magpul Pmag.

$675 - Rifle with stock (all black) setup - Palmetto State Armory stock and grip, DPMS hand guard, and 1 Black Magpul Pmag.

title: For Sale:  WWII BRITISH ENFIELD NO. 5 MK. 1 **BSA** "Jungle Carbine" RIFLE 1945 DATED .303 CAL.
location: I-30 and I-430, Little Rock, Arkansas
postcontent: Up for sale is a very good condition original WWII British Enfield No. 5 Mk. 1, which was referred to as the "Jungle Carbine" by British troops at the end of WWII.  This particular rifle was made by "BSA" Birmingham Small Arms Company.  BSA rifles are the rarest of the Jungle Carbines because only about 80,000 were ever made compared to 170,000 by the Royal Ordnance Factory.  The rifle is dated "1945" on the side of the receiver and it is also marked "No. 5 Mk. 1"  BSA rifles also had the marking M/47 C on the side of the receiver like this one has.  The serial also starts with a "B" designating it a BSA rifle.  Overall, it is in excellent shape for its age and rarity! These original WWII Jungle Carbines are very rare and hard to find.  They are much harder to find than regular Enfields.  The bore is in very good condition with strong rifling and grooves.  This rifle will make a great shooter.  I will do a bill of sale requiring DLN and date of birth of Arkansas residents. I will also accept a Concealed Weapons License number on the bill of sale which would eliminate a DLN and Date of Birth. I will ship the rifle anywhere in the country to an FFL.

title: For Sale/Trade:  German Mauser K-98 / Yugoslavian Zastava Mauser M-98 8mm Rifle w/ 175 Rounds Ammo
postcontent:
A brief history:
Yugoslavian Model M-98 Mauser Rifle
Not to be confused with any of the other Yugoslavian Mauser Rifles, the M-98 is the only one of the Yugo Mauser rifles that originates in Germany. These rifles were used by the Nazis during the occupation of Yugoslavia during WWII, and were captured when Yugoslavia liberated itself in 1944 (the only European country to accomplish this without aid from foreign armies). Another source of WWII German K-98s to Yugoslavia at the time came in the form of war reparations from Germany after the cessation of hostilities. 

Following liberation, Yugoslavia's military was understandably critically short of weapons. One means of resolving the shortage was through overhauling and remarking captured German rifles, which were after all, quite similar to those the Yugoslavians usually employed at the time.

Some advertisers list the Yugo M-98 as 'German M98k Mausers' however we deem this as potentially misleading because original markings have been tampered with and as a result do not include the words 'WWII German' in the model name. The reasons for this involve the arsenal refinishing and remarking of these rifles: original maker's markings and production year have been ground off the receiver and replaced with the Yugoslavian crest. In some cases serial numbers have added and/or removed, and some Yugo M-98s will bear the 'Preduzece 44' markings of the Zastava arsenal where the rifles were overhauled.

This rifle has the crest and the Preduzece 44 stamping.  It is in extremely good condition with no cracks in the wood and good clean blueing.  It has a sling that was made to simulate the original.  

I will include 175 rounds of ammunition

title: For Sale:  HK MR556 AR15 M4 5.56 .223 NT COLT LWRC 223 NIB
postcontent: The mr556a1 A direct descendent of the HK416, the MR556A1 is a semi-automatic rifle developed by Heckler & Koch as a premium level commercial/civilian firearm with match rifle capability. Like the HK416, the MR556A1 is a major product improvement over conventional AR-type carbines and rifles. The MR556A1 uses the HK proprietary gas piston operating system, employing a piston and a solid operating “pusher” rod in place of the gas tube normally found in AR15/M16/M4-style firearms. This method of operation virtually eliminates malfunctions that are common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. This is the same key feature critical to the success of the HK416 rifles used by leading military and law enforcement customers. The MR556A1 is produced in the USA using American and German made components.
